"German authorities have signaled that they would certify the pipeline, which is completed and awaits an operational license from Germany. But the German authorization, expected no later than January 8, 2022, will then need a review of the European Commission, which is non-binding but has to find whether the pipeline and its operation complies with EU rules. The EU has two months to decide and another two months to stall a decision, which could push the first actual gas flows on Nord Stream 2 to well beyond the winter season in Europe, to May 8"

Katja Yafimava has again summarized the current situation and the possible scenarios as of November 3, in a paper for the Oxford Energy Institute titled "Nord Steam 2: on the verge of sending gas to Europe" [1, 2]. The situation has not changed much since my summary of her previous report of October 19 [3], apart from an announcement by the relevant German ministry which I have also reported here [4] . The Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline is now finished, but Gazprom remains vague about when it will go into operation – probably in the coming months. Apart from the technical checks and testing there is an issue of permissions that need to be granted by the EU before it can start work, but these permissions will eventually be issued after a round of haggling. There is no doubt that the pipeline will go into operation, but the conditions remains up in the air. Under the EU’s third energy package it is possible that Gazprom will have to give up control of half the pipeline’s capacity to someone else – but that someone could be another Russian gas producing company like Rosneft (which certainly wants this job). And the pipeline is needed as the heating season is due to start next month and gas supplies are well below the historical averages, which has driven the price above $700 per thousand cubic meters for the first time ever.

I am forecasting a lowering of expectation of gas delivery, due to the official certification of the pipeline by the German authorities. The construction of the pipeline is now complete with Gazprom hoping to commence gas supplies by October 2021. According to S&P Global Platts, BNetxA have stated that documents for the required unbundling rules that dictate pipeline owners to be different from gas suppliers to ensure fair competition (EU Rules), were still being reviewed. Once the BNetxA have published a draft decision, it then goes to the European Commission and finally to the German regulator for a final decision. This could take four months which takes the date passed January 1, 2022. It is possible for gas to flow with the draft decision and perhaps political/economic pressure could be applied by German industry. Although EU bureaucracy should manage to delay the process.

They say construction is complete and they're just waiting for the okey-dokey from the regulatory authorities. One never knows, of course, how hard those authorities are planning to ponder such a question, but I think political intervention is unlikely as long as Gazprom checks all the EU and German boxes expeditiously.
